body_html:
tf.acos does not return a node in the graph, it creates a node in the graph and returns a [tf.Tensor]
(https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/Tensor) Python object that is a handle to the output of that operation. For example, in the snippet:

x = tf.acos(tf.constant(1))
y = tf.cos(x)

The x refers to the value (the "Tensor") that is flowing on the "edges" between the "acos" and "cos" nodes.

Hope that helps.

body:
`tf.acos` does not return a node in the graph, it creates a node in the graph and returns a [`tf.Tensor`]
(https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/Tensor) Python object that is a handle to the output of that operation. For example, in the snippet:

```python
x = tf.acos(tf.constant(1))
y = tf.cos(x)
```

The `x` refers to the value (the "Tensor") that is flowing on the "edges" between the "acos" and "cos" nodes.

Hope that helps.
